<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tudjman, Opposition Discuss Parliament Changes </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tudjman, Opposition Discuss Parliament Changes </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1705134094 Zagreb VJESNIK in Serbo-Croatian 17 May 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> AU1705134094 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb VJESNIK </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [HINA report: "Interparty Agreement Possible"] </F>
  [Text] Zagreb -- At the invitation of Croatian President 
Franjo Tudjman, a meeting of the presidents of the parliamentary 
parties and the presidents of the independent clubs of deputies 
was held on Monday to discuss a proposal of the Croatian 
Democratic Community [HDZ] regarding the need for the election 
of new chairmen of the Sabor chambers, bearing in mind that 
Stipe Mesic and Josip Manolic had left the majority party (HDZ) 
and formed their own party of the Croatian Independent Democrats 
(HND). They discussed the need for changes in the parliamentary 
commissions in light of the newly emerged party breakdown of the 
Sabor, the bureau of the president of the Republic has reported. 
The only person not to turn up at the meeting was HND President 
Stipe Mesic. 
  The representatives of the parties agreed on the need to 
resolve the highlighted problems in a democratic manner, in 
observation of the rules of the statute and the rules of 
procedure, and if possible, with an interparty agreement. It 
was, thus, agreed to continue the consultations, is stated at 
the end of a statement by the bureau of the president. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

