<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moravcik Says Stability Pact Not Like Munich </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Moravcik Says Stability Pact Not Like Munich </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1705155094 Bratislava SME in Slovak 15 May 94 pp 1-2 </F>
<F P=103> AU1705155094 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava SME </F>
<F P=105>  Slovak </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Prime Minister Jozef Moravcik by Maria </F>
Hluchanova; place and date not given: "Talks on Economic 
Cooperation Will Dominate"] 
  [Excerpts] Slovak Prime Minister Jozef Moravcik will depart 
for an official visit to the French Republic tomorrow. In this 
context, we asked him for an interview. [passage omitted] 
  [Hluchanova] What attitude will you adopt, on behalf of 
Slovakia, toward the stability pact, and how will you justify it? 
  [Moravcik] I have been informed about the results of expert 
talks on this issue that were held in Athens on 10-11 May 1994. 
At these talks, we succeeded in pushing through our standpoint, 
which has opened the path for Slovakia's active participation 
[in the conference on the stability pact to be held in Paris in 
late May]. The only question that remains open is that of the 
modalities of this participation. Regarding the voices that the 
stability pact may lead to a new Munich or a new Vienna 
Arbitrage [in November 1938, by which southern Slovakia was 
ceded to Hungary], I would like to stress that this is 
completely out of the question because one of the conditions I 
have laid down is that the principle of the inviolability and 
unchangeability of borders be fully respected and included in 
the document. This implies an advantageous starting point for 
further negotiations on our part. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

