<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Milosevic Issues Statement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Milosevic Issues Statement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1705160794 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1424 GMT 17 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1705160794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 17 May (TANJUG) -- In his talks today with 
David Owen and Thorvald Stoltenberg, cochairmen of the 
conference on the former Yugoslavia, Serbian President Slobodan 
Milosevic said peace was in the interest of all people and all 
nations in the Yugoslav area. 
  According to a statement issued by the Serbian president's 
office, Milosevic stressed that Serbia wholeheartedly supports 
the agreement on ending all hostilities in the former Yugoslav 
republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina. The question of a political 
solution and territorial demarcation should, according to 
Milosevic, be discussed with representatives of the Serb people 
from Bosnia, who are directly concerned, in exactly the same way 
as are the Muslims and Croats in this former Yugoslav republic. 
  Since all elements of the agreement on an overall end to 
hostilities in the former Bosnia-Herzegovina were discussed with 
UN and UN Protection Forces [UNPROFOR] delegations in Belgrade 
on 22 April, Milosevic believes that all obstacles and problems 
in reaching [as received] an agreement on ending the hostilities 
can only have been caused by the so-called Bosnia-Herzegovina 
Army. He believes that the international community is again 
facing a challenge -- either to behave in an impartial way or to 
apply a policy of double standards to the parties in the 
conflict. 
  Yugoslav Foreign Minister Vladislav Jovanovic attended the 
talks. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

