<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Granic Upbeat on International Status </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Granic Upbeat on International Status </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1705192494 Zagreb HTV Television in Serbo-Croatian 1730 
GMT 17 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1705192494 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb HTV Television </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Croatia's international position has recently 
improved significantly -- this conclusion was reached by Mate 
Granic, deputy prime minister and foreign minister, the Croatian 
ambassadors to the United Nations, the European Union, the CSCE, 
and the Council of Europe, and by members of the Foreign Policy 
Committee of the Croatian Parliament's Chamber of 
Representatives. 
  [Correspondent] The Republic of Croatia has never been held 
in higher international esteem, says Minister Granic. There are 
no serious pressures from foreign countries. We have completely 
adjusted our position regarding Bosnia-Herzegovina to that of 
the international community. The Washington agreement is the 
foundation for future relations between the Croats and Muslims. 
Now that the Vienna agreement has been signed, there are no 
significant obstacles to the establishment of the 
Bosnia-Herzegovina federation. 
  As regards the UN protected areas [UNPA's], the cease-fire 
agreement has been fully implemented by the Croatian side. We 
expect that the Serbian side will do the same. After that the 
talks on economic issues and, finally, on political issues 
should follow. 
  [Begin Granic recording] Our relations with Serbia are 
perhaps the only thing I would like to underline. If Serbia 
does not make its position regarding the UNPA's very clear, we 
will insist on the sanctions, in keeping with [UN Security 
Council] Resolution 871. There will be no meeting in Belgrade 
and I will not travel there until the agreed conditions are met. 
[end recording] [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

