<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Klaus on Temelin Issue, Relations With Austria </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Klaus on Temelin Issue, Relations With Austria </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1305193794 Prague CTK in English 1742 GMT 13 May 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1305193794 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, May 13 (CTK) -- Czech Premier Vaclav Klaus 
admitted today that the issue of the Temelin nuclear power plant 
in south Bohemia, some 80 kilometers from the Austrian border, 
complicated Czech-Austrian relations. Klaus made his remarks at 
a meeting with Austrian Vice-Chancellor Erhard Busek. Busek had 
stressed the sensitivity of the question for Austrian citizens, 
Klaus told journalists. 
  "On the other hand the vice-chancellor is also aware that 
the 
Czech power situation is not easy, no easy solutions exist and 
that the issue cannot be allowed to complicate and hamper future 
Czech-Austrian relations," Klaus said. 
  He said he discussed with Busek measures aimed at the 
revival 
of mutual relations, including those on an official level. He 
pointed to his planned visit to the Salzburg festival in August 
at which he could meet several Austrian politicians. Klaus 
stressed that Czech and Austrian views on many European problems 
were "very close." 

</TEXT>

