<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   SNS Leaders Plan Independent Role in Vote </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SNS Leaders Plan Independent Role in Vote </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1505142894 Prague CTK in English 1326 GMT 15 May 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1505142894 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, May 14 (CTK) -- The leadership of the 
Slovak National Party (SNS) decided to recommend to its June 
congress to enter the autumn parliamentary elections 
independently, not in coalition with its current ally, the 
Movement for a Democratic Slovakia (HZDS), the SNS Chairman Jan 
Slota announced yesterday. The SNS leadership will recommend to 
the June congress to return to the the original statutes which 
prefer the national to the civic principle, Slota said. The 
April poll showed that the SNS (9 deputies in the 150-member 
Slovak Parliament) is favoured by some four per cent of voters, 
while the HZDS by 32 per cent. 
  The observers have suggested that the decision is connected 
with alleged internal feuds regarding Slota. He enjoys the 
reputation of a radical politician, not acceptable for Meciar's 
HZDS. The press has speculated that the June SNS congress could 
lead to a split into three factions. One could be headed by 
Slota, the second by deputy chairmen of former Meciar's 
government Jan Prokes and Marian Andel, and the third by Juraj 
Molnar who has recently espoused the Pan-Slavic idea of the 
Russian politician Vladimir Zhirinovsky. 

</TEXT>

