<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   First-Quarter Trade, Prices Assessed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    First-Quarter Trade, Prices Assessed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1905093794 Prague HOSPODARSKE NOVINY in Czech 13 May 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> AU1905093794 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague HOSPODARSKE NOVINY </F>
<F P=105>  Czech </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Slovaks Balance the First Quarter"] </F>
  [Text] Bratislava--Over the first three months of this 
year, Slovakia reached a surplus of 2.2 billion Slovak korunas 
[Sk] in trade with the Czech Republic, Stefan Condik, chairman 
of the Statistical Office of the Slovak Republic (SUSR), said at 
a news conference in Bratislava yesterday. Imports from the 
Czech Republic amounted to Sk14.3 billion during this period 
(30.2 percent of the total imports to Slovakia), and goods worth 
Sk16.5 billion were exported to the Czech Republic (37.9 percent 
of total Slovak exports). These data do not include reexports, 
however. Using the statistical method according to the trading 
country, Slovakia had a deficit of Sk3.6 billion in trade with 
the Czech Republic. 
  Stefan Condik said that the trend of deceleration of the 
growth of prices emerged in Slovakia in the first quarter of 
1994. Inflation rose on the whole, according to the SUSR data 
for the first quarter, by 2.6 percent in comparison with 
December of last year, and it was to a certain degree affected 
by the development in wages. Wages in industry rose by 16.3 
percent from February to reach Sk6,291, and in construction by 
15.7 percent, to Sk5,919. Salaries in retailing rose 10 percent, 
to Sk4,714, and in transport 6.7 percent, to Sk6,119. The 
average monthly wages for the entire national economy reached 
the amount of Sk5,400 in the first quarter, which is 14 to 15 
percent (Sk700) more than in the same period last year. 
  There were 370,500 unemployed in Slovakia in March, which is 
approximately 14.7 percent of those able to work. In comparison 
with February (14.8 percent rate of unemployment), the number of 
unemployed declined by 5,500 people. 
  The effect of the introduction of the import surcharge 
became 
obvious in March, and the trade deficit rose by only Sk35 
million. The overall balance of trade ended with a deficit of 
Sk3.7 billion for the quarter. Goods worth Sk47.2 billion were 
imported to Slovakia during the first three months of the year, 
which is 1 percent more than in the same period of 1993. 
Exports amounted to Sk43.5 billion, which is a 2.6-percent drop 
in the year-to-year comparison. 
  The value of foreign capital in the Slovak economy reached 
Sk11.5 billion at the end of March. That is a 6.7-percent 
increase in comparison with the last quarter of 1993. Austria 
is responsible for the main share of investments in the Slovak 
economy (23.4 percent), followed by Germany (21 percent). The 
Czech Republic (whose share rose to 13 percent) recently passed 
the United States (12.1) percent). Foreign capital is invested 
in 5,719 companies. Since the beginning of the year, 35 firms 
with foreign capital participation closed down in Slovakia, and 
another 80 firms are being liquidated. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
