<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Krajisnik: Cochairmen Agree on Maps </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Krajisnik: Cochairmen Agree on Maps </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1905091894 Belgrade TANJUG in English 0905 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1905091894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, May 19 (TANJUG) -- The speaker of the 
Bosnian Serb republic parliament, Momcilo Krajisnik, said on 
Wednesday that the cochairmen of the conference on the former 
Yugoslavia, Lord Owen and Thorvald Stoltenberg, have agreed with 
the stand of the leadership of the Bosnian Serb republic (R.S.) 
that the maps, determined in Geneva on May 13, significantly 
encroach upon the integrity of the R.S. and promised they would 
work on a better solution. 
  The formula of the European Union on the division of the 
former Yugoslav republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina was accepted at 
the ministerial meeting in Geneva, where agreement on a joint 
strategy towards the conflict in Bosnia-Herzegovina was reached. 
Under the E.U. formula, 51 percent of the total 
Bosnia-Herzegovina territory would go to the Bosnian 
Moslem-Croat federation, agreed in Washington under U.S. 
pressure, while the Serbs would get the remaining 49 percent. 
  "With regret I conveyed to the cochairmen the conference on 
former Yugoslavia, Lord Owen and Stoltenberg, the stand that the 
presented maps seriously encroach upon the vital interests of 
the Serb people because they have been made to satisfy the 
Moslem-Croat side and not all three sides," Krajisnik said in a 
statement to Radio Jagodina. 
  Taking into consideration that the proposed maps encroach 
upon the integrity of the Bosnian Serb Republic and the fact 
that they are a poor solution if quality is taken into 
consideration, it will be, as Krajisnik said, very difficult to 
arrive to a just solution, i.e. a consensus. 
  The cochairmen promised they would convey the objections 
voiced by the Serb side to the contact group for Bosnia, 
Krajisnik said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-55675 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu097_i_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-097 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  18 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zubak Opposes `Hasty' Moves in Federation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Zubak Opposes `Hasty' Moves in Federation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1805153394 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1300 GMT 18 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1805153394 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Bosnian Croat leader Kresimir Zubak by Amir </F>
Hodzic in Geneva; date not given -- recorded] 
  [Text] [Hodzic] Mr. Zubak, [words indistinct] of the 
negotiations between the Bosniak and the Croatian sides? 
  [Zubak] I think that the issues that we discussed in Vienna 
were in fact the most difficult ones, and the most testing ones 
for the implementation of the Washington Agreement, that is, for 
the implementation of the Federation Constitution. This is of 
utmost significance since we have now overcome the most 
difficult problems. 
  [Hodzic] You were here in Geneva for the meeting of the 
contact group for Bosnia-Herzegovina. How would you comment on 
their joint statement? 
  [Zubak] That communique issued by the European Union, that 
is, [words indistinct] and the United States, is completely in 
line with what we agreed on. However, it is questionable in 
those parts where it refers to possible territory for the 
Federation after the demarcation, that is, if the [word 
indistinct] accept to join it. As far as I personally am 
concerned, I think that the Federation has to be a geopolitical 
whole, to be tenable, that is, that it can function as a state 
community. It has to have communications and road connections, 
it has to be economically strong enough to provide security for 
its citizens, and a standard of living that is normal, that is, 
a standard of living that is equal to the European one. 
  [Hodzic] In your view, what are the next top priority tasks 
[words indistinct] in order to implement the Federation 
Constitution and the Vienna Agreement on the ground? 
  [Zubak] You see, I have maintained [pauses] I am one of 
those who is against deadlines of six months for the 
implementation of the Constitution since I believe that this is 
unrealistic. I still believe that [word indistinct] the cease- 
fire holds, and then we can [words indistinct] for the 
Federation. Anything hasty or ill-prepared [words indistinct] 
could possibly cause incidents [words indistinct]. That is why 
I believe that we should -- as agreed in Vienna -- first adopt 
[word indistinct] at the Constitutional Assembly, then explain 
to the people the advantages of the new political and 
territorial demarcation, and then go into further implementation 
of the Vienna Agreement. 
  [Hodzic] Do you think there will be problems on the ground 
in implementing the Vienna Agreement? 
  [Zubak] Well, you see, there is a need to talk to the 
people, give them information, provide them with explanations 
[words indistinct] the Constitution, and everything that we have 
agreed on. Once the people are told, I do not believe that 
there will be any problems with the implementation, either with 
the Bosniak people or the Croatian people. 
  [Hodzic] Thank you very much. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

