<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbian `Racket' Described </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Serbian `Racket' Described </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1805163594 Paris AFP in English 1606 GMT 18 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1805163594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Sarajevo, May 18 (AFP) -- Eleven French aid 
workers detained for over a month by Bosnian Serbs for alleged 
arms trafficking were freed and flown out of Sarajevo on 
Wednesday [18 May] after payment of $44,000. In Paris, a 
spokeswoman for the charity group Premiere Urgence (Emergency 
Aid), which sent them into Bosnia-Hercegovina, denied that the 
4,000 dollars a head paid by the organisation for their release 
was a ransom. 
  The sum was "too small to be considered as a ransom," said 
spokeswoman Pascale de Lomas. She said rather that the money 
was "bail" which allowed the Bosnian Serbs to "save face." The 
Serbs' demand for payment, which "resembles a racket," had 
caused much heart-searching at the charity, she added. [passage 
omitted] 
  A communique issued by the French Foreign Ministry said the 
release came after "direct pressure from Paris and (Bosnia) on 
the main parties concerned." French Foreign Minister Alain 
Juppe had several contacts with the authorities of rump 
Yugoslavia and sent the foreign ministry's general secretary, 
Bertrand Dufourq, to Belgrade to negotiate a release. 
Ambassador Jacolin had daily contacts with the group, the 
statement added. 
  The Foreign Ministry said contacts had also been made with 
France's main western partners as well as Russia, European Union 
president Greece, and the cochairman of the peace conference on 
the former Yugoslavia, Lord Owen, and UN Secretary General 
Butrus Butrus-Ghali to help end the aid workers' 40-day ordeal. 
France "thanks those who helped," the statement added. [passage 
omitted] 
  On Tuesday, a day before the release, Patricia Ettouati, the 
only woman in the group, wrote to the bishop of the Normandy 
town of Evreux, Jacques Gaillot, that the Serbs were "champions 
in psychological destruction." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

