<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Simic Urges UNPROFOR To Show Impartiality </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Simic Urges UNPROFOR To Show Impartiality </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1805170294 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1632 GMT 18 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1805170294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, May 18 (TANJUG) -- The vice-president of 
the Yugoslav Federal Government, Zeljko Simic, said on Wednesday 
[18 May] that the U.N. Protection Force (UNPROFOR) should once 
again adopt an impartial position in performing its peacekeeping 
mission on the territory of the former Yugoslavia. During talks 
with UNPROFOR director for civil affairs, Serge de Melle, and 
with the coordinator for civil affairs at the Belgrade 
headquarters of the "blue helmets", Vladislam Gerasev, Simic 
said that UNPROFOR should do everything possible to inform the 
U.N. and world public opinion in a timely manner about the real 
situation in war-torn regions. 
  By so doing UNPROFOR will restore the credibility it needs 
to 
take part in appeasing tension and establish lasting peace in 
the former Bosnia-Herzegovina, he said. The Yugoslav Ministry 
of Information announced that the representatives of UNPROFOR 
informed simic about the implementation of the agreement on the 
cessation of hostilities in the region of Gorazde, a Moslem 
enclave in the east of the former Yugoslav republic of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina [B-H] in which war has been raging between 
local Serbs, Croats and Moslems for over two years. 
  The agreement was signed here on April 22 by representatives 
of the U.N. and the Bosnian Serb republic, a state of Bosnian 
Serbs. 
  Simic told UNPROFOR representatives that the civil war in 
B-H 
should not be viewed only from the angle of certain hotbeds, 
such as Gorazde, since there are other areas, such as Brcko (in 
the north-east of B-H) which, he said, are potentially more 
dangerous and which are directly provoked by the Moslem side 
whose political and military acts are often kept secret and 
hushed up. Simic pointed out that Bosnian Serbs have objective 
reasons for dissastifaction and caution towards UNPROFOR due to 
certain indiscretions committed by the "blue helmets". He cited 
as an example the direct participation of the Nordic battalion 
of UNPROFOR on the side of Moslems in clashes in the region of 
Tuzla (north-east B-H), last week. Simic stressed that the 
Yugoslav Government will continue to extend its help to UNPROFOR 
to stabilize the situation in B-H in order to create 
pre-conditions to continue talks for finding a lasting political 
solution to the conflict, in accordance with the foreign policy 
of the country. Finally, Simic expressed his gratitude to 
UNPROFOR representatives and to the special envoy of U.N. 
secretary general, Yasushi Akashi, for their efforts to overcome 
the crisis in B-H. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-55708 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu097_i_94001" </HT>


