<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister Bemoans Russia's Status in `Partnership' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Minister Bemoans Russia's Status in `Partnership' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1905131594 Warsaw TV Polonia Network in Polish 1000 GMT 19 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1905131594 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw TV Polonia Network </F>
<F P=105>  Polish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] An inaugural meeting of the government Committee for 
Defense Matters has been in progress for an hour. The committee 
is discussing a report on the state of Poland's defense prepared 
by the Ministry of National Defense. Defense Minister Piotr 
Kolodziejczyk said before the meeting that it would be a bad 
thing if the NATO states give Russia a privileged position in 
the Partnership for Peace program. 
  [Begin Kolodziejczyk recording] Such a solution would 
contradict the idea of the Partnership. It is true that Russia 
still remains a superpower and has the right to negotiate 
various treaties with the United States and with NATO as a 
whole, but not within the framework of the Partnership for Peace 
initiative, which would then become doubtful. [end recording] 
  According to Minister Kolodziejczyk, the reduction of 
Russian 
troops from 200,000 to 25,000 in the Kaliningrad district may be 
carried out soon. 

</TEXT>

