<F P=100> THE FORMER YUGOSLAV REPUBLIC OF MACEDONIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crvenkovski Views Talks With Greece </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Crvenkovski Views Talks With Greece </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1805205294 Skopje MIC in English 18 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1805205294 </F>
<F P=104>  Skopje MIC </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Crvenkovski Moderate Optimist"] </F>
  [Text] Reserved optimism for the course of the 
Macedonian-Greek negotiations was expressed by Macedonia's [The 
Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia -- FYROM] Foreign 
Relations Minister Stevo Crvenkovski in his statement for 
MAKPRESS after yesterday's one hour meeting in New York with the 
UN and U.S. mediators Cyrus Vance and Matthew Nimitz. 
  Reminding of the agreement reached with the [words 
indistinct] details of the negotiations, Crvenkovski did not 
want to comment on the basis for this feeling that "there are 
possibilities" that things will move from the standstill. 
  Commenting on the proposal for a new name, "Northern 
Macedonia," that was allegedly made by the American mediator 
Matthew Nimitz, Crvenkovski said: "In this phase we have as yet 
not reached any concrete proposals, especially not about the 
name," but ways are being sought out to continue the dialogue 
which is in the interest of both sides. 
  It is reported from New York that, depending on the results 
of the meeting with Vance scheduled for late last night, 
Minister Crvenkovski may leave for Washington for several 
meetings. 
  Up until today no progress has been made, stated yesterday 
in 
New York the Greek ambassador Zaharakis after the meeting with 
Cyrus Vance. Zaharakis denied the speculations in the press 
according to which the U.S. mediator Nimitz presented proposals 
for the name: "New" or "Northern" Macedonia. Replying to a 
question Zaharakis said: "Mr. Nimitz has not presented any 
proposals, he simply participates in the procedure for the 
exchange of opinion." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

