<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Journalists Interview Tudjman </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russian Journalists Interview Tudjman </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1905211894 Zagreb HTV Television in Serbo-Croatian 1730 
GMT 19 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1905211894 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb HTV Television </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Croatia is satisfied with the development of 
relations with the Russian Federation and wants to have friendly 
relations in all areas, President of the Republic of Croatia 
Franjo Tudjman said in an interview with reporters of leading 
Russian media in Zagreb today. 
  Answering questions by reporters from Russian state 
television, ITAR-TASS, and the newspaper MOSKOVSKIYE NOVOSTI, 
President Tudjman stressed that relations which existed before 
the formation of the sovereign, independent, and democratic 
Croatia only continued following the establishment of diplomatic 
ties between the two countries. He said that Russia had so far 
played a positive role in the search for a political solution to 
the crisis in the region. He particularly stressed the role of 
Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev and the Russian president's 
special envoy, Vitaliy Churkin, at the Geneva conference. They 
tried to exert influence on Serbia and the Serbs in Croatia to 
honor Croatia's internationally recognized borders. 
  President Tudjman also spoke in favorable terms about the 
economic relations between the two countries and said that great 
successes had been made in that sphere. 

</TEXT>

