<H3> <TI>   Gligorov, Akashi Discuss Economic Problems </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Gligorov, Akashi Discuss Economic Problems </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1905195994 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1755 GMT 19 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1905195994 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Skopje, 19 May (TANJUG) -- "My visit to Macedonia, 
in the company of French General de Laprsle, UNPROFOR [UN 
Protection Forces] commander for former Yugoslavia, is aimed at 
gaining a first-hand insight into the country's internal and 
external stability," head of UNPROFOR's mission in former 
Yugoslavia, Japanese diplomat Yasushi Akashi, said this 
afternoon. 
  We had a very fruitful discussion with President Kiro 
Gligorov and Defense Minister Vlado Popovski. We wished to hear 
their opinions, which will also help the United Nations 
determine future moves -- especially as regards the stability of 
borders and the improvement of economic and political stability, 
Akashi said. 
  I discovered, unfortunately, that Macedonia was in an 
unenviable economic situation due to its strict adherence to the 
economic sanctions against Yugoslavia, and because of the 
embargo imposed by Greece against Macedonia. I will convey 
President Gligorov's message to UN Secretary-General Butrus 
Butrus-Ghali. President Gligorov has suggested that the 
Greek-Macedonian dispute be examined by the UN Security Council. 
Akashi particularly stressed that the talks provided an 
opportunity for a thorough analysis of the situation along 
Macedonia's borders -- especially the sections monitored by 
UNPROFOR. 
  Akashi also met UNPROFOR representatives in Macedonia in the 
course of his one-day visit. 

</TEXT>

