<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Receives Yugoslav Envoy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Minister Receives Yugoslav Envoy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1905201594 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1700 GMT 19 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1905201594 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Mate Granic, Croatian deputy prime minister and 
minister of foreign affairs, today received Veljko Knezevic, 
head of the Bureau of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia in 
Zagreb, the Croatian Ministry of Foreign Affairs has announced. 
Their talks focused on the current situation in the UN 
protected areas in Croatia as well as on the implementation of 
the Zagreb cease-fire agreement signed on 29 March. The 
Croatian foreign minister and his guest concluded that 
negotiations between the Croatian Government and the Serbs from 
the UN protected areas should continue as soon as possible. 
  They also discussed the possibilities and conditions for the 
speedy normalization of relations between the Republic of 
Croatia and the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia. In their talks 
Minister Granic and envoy Knezevic discussed developments in 
former Yugoslavia. In this context it was said that 
negotiations between the Bosnia-Hercegovina federation and the 
Bosnian Serbs should start soon. The Croatian foreign minister 
emphasized that these negotiations and a cease-fire would enable 
talks on a definite territorial and constitutional arrangement 
for Bosnia-Herzegovina to be resumed as soon as possible. 
  Minister Granic also pointed out that searching for a 
solution to the problem of UN protected areas in Croatia had to 
be undertaken simultaneously with the negotiations on 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

