<H3> <TI>   Ministry Denies Report on Troops in B-H </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ministry Denies Report on Troops in B-H </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1905144794 Sofia BTA in English 1322 GMT 19 May 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1905144794 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia BTA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sofia, May 19 (BTA) -- A Foreign Ministry spokesman 
today denied a REUTER report from Ankara, concerning a stand 
taken by Bulgarian Foreign Minister Stanislav Daskalov on the 
commitment of Turkish troops to UNPROFOR [UN Protection Forces] 
in Bosnia-Herzegovina. At a news conference in Ankara, cited as 
a source by the authoritative news agency, Foreign Minister 
Daskalov confirmed Bulgaria's principled position against the 
involvement of neighbouring and Balkan countries in UNPROFOR in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, says a press release received at BTA. It 
was also stressed that this position was directed neither 
against Turkey nor against any other country in the region, the 
spokesman said. 
  On May 17 REUTER reported: "Bulgarian Foreign Minister 
Stanislav Daskalov said Bulgaria in principle opposed the 
involvement of Balkan countries in the conflict but did not 
object to Turkey sending troops to join a UN peacekeeping force 
in Bosnia." 

</TEXT>

