<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   NATO's `Special Relations' With Russia Noted </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    NATO's `Special Relations' With Russia Noted </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1905162294 Prague CTK in English 1437 GMT 19 May 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1905162294 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague May 19 (CTK) -- The Czech Foreign Ministry 
will not react to unofficial reports that NATO has conceded to 
pressure from Russia and offered it "special relations" with 
NATO alongside participation in the Partnership for Peace 
programme. Ministry spokesman Vit Kurfurst told CTK no official 
information on the offer had been received from Brussels. 
  Kurfurst reminded reporters of Foreign Minister Josef 
Zieleniec's speech at the Charles University Law Faculty in 
Prague a month ago when he "said clearly that we signed the 
Partnership for Peace in the form of 16+1 (i.e. the 16 NATO 
states plus the Czech Republic), and not 16+1+Russia". 
  At his meeting with Ukrainian Foreign Minister Anatoliy 
Zlenko on March 17, Zieleniec said that if Russia insisted on a 
special status in the Partnership for Peace programme, as 
Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev had done several times, 
new negotiations on the programme would have to be launched. He 
said the Czech Republic was satisfied with the form of the 
programme and did not regard alteration as realistic. 
  According to unofficial information from Brussels, NATO's 
special relations with Russia are separate from the Partnership 
for Peace, offered by NATO in January to former communist bloc 
countries with an unspecified possibility of future alliance 
membership. 
  Besides the Czech Republic, 17 countries have so far joined 
the Partnership programme. At the beginning of the year, 
Russian representatives expressed willingness to join the scheme 
but later revised their view and accused NATO of not taking 
sufficient account of Russia's status as a great power. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-55761 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu098__a94008" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-098-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  15 May 1994 </DATE1>

