<H3> <TI>   Free Democrats To Continue Election Strategy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Free Democrats To Continue Election Strategy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1805074394 Budapest MTI in English 1754 GMT 17 May 94 -- 
FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1805074394 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, 17 May (MTI) -- The Alliance of Free 
Democrats (SZDSZ) will not change the tone of its campaign 
preceding the May 29 run-off of the parliamentary elections. 
Instead of slinging mud at its main rival, the Hungarian 
Socialist Party (MSZP), it strives to emphasize differences 
between the two parties and demonstrate why it would be 
advantageous for the country to vote for the Free Democrats, 
SZDSZ Chairman Ivan Peto told a party meeting at Budaors today. 
  "The SZDSZ fared well in the first round and retained almost 
all of its electoral base," Peto said, attributing his party's 
success to its unique reliability and well-founded policy. 
  "In the first round, voters cast their ballots on parties 
rather than candidates because they wanted to dismiss the 
governing coalition. Now they will rather consider which 
candidate would better fit the post," Peto said. 
  "For this reason, it would be advantageous for SZDSZ 
candidates to expound their views to the broadest possible 
audience, in various forums covered by local TV stations. In 
this competition, the SZDSZ has excellent chances because it has 
fielded plenty of highly qualified candidates," Peto said. 

</TEXT>

