<F P=101> Hungary </F>
<H3> <TI>   Coalition Prospects Viewed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Coalition Prospects Viewed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1905201394 Budapest MTI in English 1802 GMT 19 May 94 -- 
FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1905201394 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, 19 May (MTI) -- It is uncertain what kind 
of governing coalition, if any, will be formed after the May 29 
run-off of the parliamentary elections. One thing is certain: 
Voters have dismissed the coalition that governed the country 
over the past four years, Gabor Kuncze, prime minister candidate 
of the Alliance of Free Democrats (SZDSZ), told a news 
conference in Papa, western Hungary, today. What will be at 
stake on May 29 is whether voters will authorize the Free 
Democrats to represent their interests with an appropriate 
weight, Kuncze said. 
  In his view, the Hungarian Democratic Forum (MDF) insists on 
a strategy which gained plenty of votes for the Hungarian 
Socialist Party (MSZP), the winner of the first round of the 
elections. 
  Failing to withdraw its candidates without any chance in the 
second round and frightening voters with a communist 
restoration, the MDF plays into the hands of the Socialists, and 
proves that it gives priority to party interests over national 
ones, Kuncze said. 
  SZDSZ campaign chief Balint Magyar, meeting reporters in 
Miskolc today, said the second round would decide whether a 
balanced political culture emerges which makes it possible to 
form a stable government and a coalition based on partnership 
for the next four years, or the MSZP gains an absolute majority 
in parliament. For a balanced governing coalition to be formed, 
the SZDSZ must fare well in the second round of the elections, 
Magyar said. 

</TEXT>

