<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Poland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pawlak Comments on Kulesza's Resignation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Pawlak Comments on Kulesza's Resignation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1605194194 Warsaw PAP in English 1919 GMT 16 May 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD1605194194 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, May 16 -- Commenting on the decision of 
Minister Michal Kulesza to resign from the post of government 
commissioner for public administration reform, Prime Minister 
Waldemar Pawlak said on Monday that he "expected more 
responsibility in these actions." Pawlak added he hoped "a 
slightly different outlook on introducing reforms might be 
helpful in working out final solutions." 
  "We are supporting decentralisation but at the same time we 
are not going to put responsibility on local governments in a 
way which is making it impossible for them to fulfil these 
tasks," the prime minister stressed, adding that for instance it 
was local governments which decided whether to take over 
schools. The prime minister also said the cabinet was 
supporting the plan to grant more powers to local authorities. 
  Commenting on Kulesza's statement that the assumptions of 
the 
socio-economic policy for the years 1994-1997 and draft laws on 
state administration prove that the cabinet is not interested in 
Poland's decentralisation, the head of the cabinet office, 
Minister Marian Strak, said: "I think that this opinion is 
resulting either from incomplete knowledge of the documents or 
ill will." Strak stressed the documents proved the cabinet 
wanted to increase powers of local governments and to 
consolidate the position of a governor. "The point is to make a 
governor a host in a province and not one of the parts of the 
state administration," he added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-55775 </DOCNO>
