<F P=101> Poland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deputy Defense Minister on Arms Industry </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Deputy Defense Minister on Arms Industry </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1305205794 Warsaw PAP in English 2028 GMT 13 May 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD1305205794 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, May 13 -- Deputy Defence Minister Jerzy 
Milewski on Friday reported to the Sejm about the main points of 
the Defence Ministry policy toward the Polish arms industry. He 
said that sixty to seventy per cent of the Defence Ministry 
orders would be placed with the home arms industry. He added 
that the Defence Ministry cannot assume responsibility for debts 
from the previous period. 
  There is an agreement between the Polish Defence Ministry 
and 
the United States Defence Department providing for promotion of 
a programme of the Polish Armed Forces modernization. The 
cooperation in this field envisages production based on U.S. 
latest technologies, Milewski said. He added that Poland had 
not concluded any other agreement with the U.S. Polish arms 
industry cooperates also with arms industries of France, Sweden 
and Israel. 
  Janusz Onyszkiewicz, the defence minister in the Hanna 
Suchocka Government, said that Poland has large facilities for 
overhauling military equipment becuase such were the tasks 
Poland performed within the Warsaw Treaty. 
  Deputies of different groupings demanded that a general 
debate on issues related to the defence be held in June. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

