<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Stability Pact `Acceptable' to Republic </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Stability Pact `Acceptable' to Republic </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1905201894 Prague CTK in English 1726 GMT 19 May 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1905201894 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava May 19 (CTK) -- The European Pact of 
Stability, or the Balladur Plan, is acceptable for Slovakia in 
its proposed form, Igor Liska from the Foreign Ministry told CTK 
today. The acceptability of the working version of the pact was 
also confirmed by Slovak Ambassador to Geneva Jan Kubis who had 
led the Slovak delegation to the talks on the pact. The pact 
has also been supported by Premier Jozef Moravcik during his 
visit to France this week. 
  Kubis said that the latest version of the document ruling 
out 
border changes suited Slovakia. Of late voices could be heard 
in Hungary urging a revision of the Slovak-Hungarian border to 
the benefit of Hungary. A strong Hungarian minority lives in 
southern Slovakia. 
  Slovakia has also welcomed the deletion of that part of the 
text which bound Slovakia and Hungary to conclude an inter-state 
treaty under the auspices of the European Union. 
  Bratislava sticks to the civic principle on ethnic 
minorities, which means that it would not recognise minorities' 
collective rights. Collective rights for ethnic minorities are 
also rejected by most Western countries. The Czech Republic 
rejects the principle as well. 
  Kubis said on Wednesday [18 May] that the Czech and Slovak 
Republics had not coordinated their policies on the pact, 
because the Czech Republic unlike Slovakia did not have any 
minority problems. Kubis also pointed out Slovak diplomacy's 
effort to broaden the pact's goals to embrace economic, 
environmental and cross-border cooperation as well. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

