<H3> <TI>   Former Minister Defends HZDS Advertisement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Former Minister Defends HZDS Advertisement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1905200594 Prague CTK in English 1712 GMT 19 May 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1905200594 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava May 19 (CTK) -- Katarina Tothova, the 
ex-minister of justice and a member of the Movement for a 
Democratic Slovakia (HZDS), does not think that public 
competition for the posts of state officials, the conditions of 
which the HZDS published in the form of an advertisement in the 
daily PRAVDA on Friday [13 May], was incorrect or even illegal. 
"Everybody may do everything which is not forbidden by the 
law," Tothova said today at a press conference of the "shadow 
cabinet" of the HZDS leader and former premier, Vladimir Meciar. 
  She said she considered it highly moral that the HZDS was 
preparing its own potential of experts, and recommended other 
parties to follow suit. She said she expected the HZDS to be 
represented in the government after the autumn elections. 
  Although polls have shown a decline in the HZDS's 
popularity, 
the movement still enjoys the highest confidence of voters (27 
percent), and has great election ambitions. 
  On Wednesday [18 May], PRAVDA rescinded the contract with 
the 
HZDS for its "not keeping to the advertising rules." The 
full-page advertisements worth almost 2.5 million crowns 
($80,600) will not be published any longer. Besides the 
conditions of public competition, they also included attacks 
against Slovak President Michal Kovac and some members of the 
present cabinet of Jozef Moravcik. 

</TEXT>

