<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll Shows Decline in Support for HZDS </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Poll Shows Decline in Support for HZDS </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1805132094 Prague CTK in English 1228 GMT 18 May 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1805132094 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava May 18 (CTK) -- If parliamentary 
elections were held now, 27 percent of voters would support for 
the Movement for a Democratic Slovakia (HZDS), according to a 
poll conducted by the Slovak Statistical Office (SU SR) whose 
results were handed to CTK today. In April, 32 percent of those 
polled said they would vote for the HZDS. The HZDS-led 
government fell in March following a parliamentary no-confidence 
vote in former Slovak Premier Vladimir Meciar. 
  The Democratic Left Party (SDL) with 16 percent support 
fares 
three percent better than in April. 
  The Christian Democratic Movement (KDH), led by ex-Premier 
Jan Carnogursky, with 11 percent support also gained three 
percent against April, followed by the coalition between 
Egyutteles and the Hungarian Christian Democratic Movement 
supported by seven percent of voters. 
  In contrast, Premier Josef Moravcik's Democratic Union of 
Slovakia (DEUS) with current support of five percent was the 
only party in the current government coalition to receive less 
voter preference than in April (seven percent). 
  The Slovak National Party (SNS) and the Greens Party would 
each obtain four percent of the vote, the Social Democratic 
Party in Slovakia (SDSS), the Slovak Workers' Party and the 
National Democratic Party -- New Alternative (NDS-NA) each three 
percent of the vote and the Democratic Party (DS) and the Party 
of Slovak Entrepreneurs and Tradespeople (SSPZ) each two percent 
of the vote. Eight percent of the respondents did not know for 
whom they would vote. 

</TEXT>

