<F P=100> BULGARIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zhelev, Party Leaders Discuss Early Elections </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Zhelev, Party Leaders Discuss Early Elections </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2005134994 Sofia Khorizont Radio Network in Bulgarian 1300 
GMT 20 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2005134994 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia Khorizont Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Bulgarian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] As we have already reported, President Zhelev this 
morning invited representatives of the parliamentary groups to a 
meeting to discuss the political situation in the country. Only 
Stefan Savov [leader of the Union of Democratic Forces 
parliamentary group] showed up for this meeting. 
  At lunchtime President Zhelev met with Professor Nikolay 
Vasilev and Georgi Kostov, representatives of the NSD [New 
Alliance for Democracy], and with Ruslan Semerdzhiev and Ivan 
Pushkarov of the Assembly for Democracy [SD]. At the meeting 
they discussed possible ways out of the present political 
situation. President Zhelev suggested that a definite date 
should be fixed for holding early parliamentary elections, 
which, in his view, should take place at the end of September or 
the beginning of October. Once this date had been determined, 
the political forces should reach an agreement on electing a 
government. During this period parliament should concentrate on 
passing the most urgent economic legislation. Two months before 
the date fixed for the elections, the government should become a 
caretaker and start preparing for early parliamentary elections. 
  President Zhelev also explained his views on the way out of 
the present political situation with Aleksandur Tomov, GOR 
[Civic Alliance for the Republic] leader. As Tomov said a few 
minutes ago after the meeting had ended, they discussed the 
possibility of signing an agreement on early parliamentary 
elections within the next 10 days and of ensuring a smooth 
transitional period until the elections are held. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-55795 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu099_b_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-099 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  20 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BULGARIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zhelev Announces Proposal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Zhelev Announces Proposal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2005165494 Sofia Khorizont Radio Network in Bulgarian 1600 
GMT 20 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2005165494 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia Khorizont Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Bulgarian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Address to the nation by Bulgarian President Zhelyu Zhelev </F>
in Sofia on 20 May -- recorded] 
  [Text] Dear compatriots: During the last few days a farce 
has developed in Bulgaria that poses a threat to the foundations 
of parliamentarianism. Guided by personal and party interests, 
many deputies have involved themselves in lobbying machinations 
and bargaining that are well on the way to finally destroying 
the people's trust in the institutions of state. I do not have 
the right to judge anyone, but I am convinced that democracy, 
apart from merely being a form of procedure, also means a sense 
of responsibility, which some people have forgotten. The 
deepening political crisis has led to a complete paralysis of 
state life. In my view, we can extract ourselves from this 
situation only with the determination of all the responsible 
political forces in the country. 
  This conviction led me to invite the chairmen of the 
parliamentary groups to a meeting. Yesterday and today I held 
talks with National Assembly Chairman Aleksandur Yordanov; with 
Stefan Savov, chairman of the parliamentary group of the Union 
of Democratic Forces [SDS]; with representatives of the NSD [New 
Alliance for Democracy] and the Independence parliamentary 
group, Georgi Kostov, Nikolay Vasilev, and Ivan Pushkarov; and 
with Aleksandur Tomov, chairman of the GOR [Civic Alliance for 
the Republic]. For reasons outside my control, no meetings took 
place with Nora Ananieva, parliamentary group leader for the BSP 
[Bulgarian Socialist Party] and its coalition, or with Ahmed 
Dogan, leader of the DPS [Movement for Rights and Freedoms] 
parliamentary group. 
  I will now propose to the nation what I proposed to the 
politicians: the reaching of an agreement between the 
parliamentary forces on early elections. The agreement should 
define the following: 
  First, the exact date of the elections. 
  Second, it should guarantee the passing of laws that will 
ensure the conclusion of the agreement on our foreign debt and 
create conditions for carrying through real reforms. 
  Third, the agreement should lead to the formation of a 
government that will enjoy the confidence of all the 
parliamentary forces, guarantee responsible government in the 
pre-election period, guarantee the fairness of the elections, 
and continue the reforms that have begun. 
  If such an agreement is concluded and such a government 
elected, I shall assume the obligation to entrust this 
government with the additional task of carrying out the 
functions of a caretaker government during the final two months 
preceding the elections. I hope that this will put an end to 
the dirty speculations concerning the role of a future caretaker 
cabinet and will enable us to emerge from the crisis, because 
what we are now putting at risk is not merely the instability of 
one government or another, of some parliament or other, but 
faith in parliamentarianism and democracy. 
  Dear compatriots, I want to believe that the parliamentary 
forces will find the courage, responsibility, and goodwill to 
conclude such an agreement on early elections, an agreement for 
preserving democracy and parliamentarianism. However, at the 
ballot box the decision lies with you. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-55796 </DOCNO>
