<F P=100> BULGARIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Berov Announces Stance on Assembly Situation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Berov Announces Stance on Assembly Situation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2005171594 Sofia Khorizont Radio Network in Bulgarian 1600 
GMT 21 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2005171594 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia Khorizont Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Bulgarian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A short time ago the Council of Ministers Press 
Center disseminated the view of Prime Minister Lyuben Berov on 
the debates in the National Assembly and the tasks facing 
parliament during the next few days. 
  The prime minister of the Republic of Bulgaria declared once 
again that the government has invested and continues to invest 
much effort in maintaining a parliamentary majority that will 
support the cabinet, without any change to its formula of a 
cabinet of experts entrusted with addressing the most important 
national tasks: combating inflation, fighting crime, settling 
the foreign debt, and other priority tasks. 
  However, with great regret, Prime Minister Berov noted that 
changes have evidently occurred in the positions held by the 
parliamentary groups, which until now have supported the 
cabinet. The prime minister intends to attempt once again to 
achieve a unification of the parliamentary groups that are now 
in opposition to one another, so as to conclude the most 
important tasks on which work has begun, which any Bulgarian 
Government is bound to complete without fail. If the prime 
minister fails to achieve this before 25 May, he will consider 
that his mission of preserving political equilibrium in the 
country has been exhausted. He is firmly convinced that unless 
this is achieved, Bulgaria is on the road to early parliamentary 
elections. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

