<F P=100> HUNGARY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Comments on MSZP Foreign Policy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Comments on MSZP Foreign Policy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2105105294 Budapest Kossuth Radio Network in Hungarian 
1000 GMT 21 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2105105294 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest Kossuth Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Hungarian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Geza Jeszenszky is worried that the Socialist Party 
[MSZP], which is leading in the elections, might want to change 
the direction of foreign policy. In a statement to a Ukrainian 
paper, the foreign minister mentioned as an example the fact 
that the Socialists, contrary to the six-party agreement, are 
urging a referendum about joining NATO. Geza Jeszenszky also 
criticized the MSZP for thinking that relations more balanced 
than the present ones are possible with Romania, Slovakia, and 
Serbia. According to the Hungarian Democratic Forum government 
member, the political directions and minority policies of these 
countries preclude rapprochement. 

</TEXT>

