<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbs Agree To Withdraw Police From Gorazde </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Serbs Agree To Withdraw Police From Gorazde </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2105194194 Paris AFP in English 1929 GMT 21 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2105194194 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, May 21 (AFP) -- Bosnian Serb forces 
agreed Saturday to pull 150 armed policemen out of the eastern 
town of Gorazde, a month after the expiry of a NATO deadline 
ordering the complete withdrawal of Serb forces from the town. 
Under the agreement, due to come into force at 6:00 p.m. (1600 
GMT) Sunday, the armed Serbs will pull back from a UN-declared 
three kilometre (two mile) exclusion zone around central 
Gorazde, UNPROFOR spokesman Major Rob Annink said here. 
  "The Bosnian Serb forces have pledged to redeploy all armed 
personnel outside the exclusion zone," Annink said. The Serbs 
also agreed to "cease all hostilities around Gorazde" and 
guaranteed UNPROFOR "complete freedom of movement" in the zone, 
he said. UNPROFOR said 150 armed Serbs had remained in Gorazde 
after the expiry of the North Atlantic Treaty Organisation 
ultimatum at the end of April. Serb sources said the men had 
remained as "policemen" to protect the town's Serb population. 
Moslem sources said they were soldiers who had changed uniform. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-55805 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu099_i_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-099 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  23 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN: Serbs Fail To Honor Accord </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN: Serbs Fail To Honor Accord </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2305121194 Paris AFP in English 1146 GMT 23 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2305121194 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, May 23 (AFP) -- Bosnian Serb commanders 
failed to pull 150 armed policemen out of the eastern town of 
Gorazde this weekend, as agreed, the UN Protection Force 
(UNPROFOR) reported Monday [23 May]. The Serbs' failure to 
abide by the Gorazde accord could torpedo the resumption of 
peace talks on Bosnia-Herzegovina, obervers warned. 
  "There is no change in the deployment inside the 
three-kilometre (two-mile) total exclusion zone," UNPROFOR 
spokesman Rob Annink said Monday, referring to a UN-declared 
exclusion zone around the valley town, which is populated mostly 
by Moslems, including thousands of refugees from Serb "ethnic 
cleansing" of nearby villages. 
  "It is a disappointment that the Bosnian Serb army did not 
react to the agreement," Major Annink said. 
  Under the agreement signed Saturday between Lieutenant 
General Sir Michael Rose, the commander of UN troops in Bosnia, 
and Bosnian Serb military leader Manojlo Milovanovic, the Serbs 
were to redeploy the 150 men outside the exclusion zone by 6:00 
p.m. (1600 GMT) Sunday. The Serbs also pledged to guarantee the 
UNPROFOR freedom of movement within a 20-kilometre (12-mile) 
heavy weapons exclusion zone around Gorazde. 
  Annink said the Serbs told UN military observers that they 
would not be granted freedom of movement within the exclusion 
zone until 570 Serbs were allowed to leave the town and the 
mainly Moslem Bosnian army withdrew from a hill overlooking 
Gorazde. He said the overall situation in Gorazde was stable 
Sunday with Bosnian Serb and Bosnian army troop movements 
reported northwest of the town. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-55806 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu099_i_94004" </HT>


