<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Muslim Side Fails To Sign Cease-Fire Annex </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Muslim Side Fails To Sign Cease-Fire Annex </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2205230194 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 2232 GMT 22 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2205230194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 22 May (TANJUG) -- The UN Protection 
Forces [UNPROFOR] command in former Bosnia-Herzegovina has 
officially informed the republic of Srpska army's main 
headquarters that the Muslim side did not sign an annex to the 
agreement on the cease-fire and cessation of hostilities within 
the 3-km zone around Gorazde which was supposed to come into 
effect at 1800 this evening. This was reported by the 
information service of the republic of Srpska army's main 
headquarters late this evening. 
  According to a public statement received by TANJUG, the 
information service points out that the annex to the agreement 
was signed by the republic of Srpska army and UNPROFOR 
representatives but that it cannot be implemented because the 
Muslim side rejected it. "By refusing to sign the agreement 
mentioned above, the Muslims have assumed all responsibility and 
once again confirmed their military option for resolving the 
crisis on the territory of the former Bosnia-Herzegovina," the 
statement issued by the information service of the main 
headquarters of the republic of Srpska army said in conclusion. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-55807 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu099_i_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-099 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  22 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army Comments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Army Comments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2205141594 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1300 GMT 22 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2205141594 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In response to the agreement on the 
demilitarization of the exclusion zone 3 km east of the Drina 
River, which UNPROFOR [UN Protection Forces] and the Serbian 
aggressor's side signed on 21 May, the press center of the 
Bosnia-Herzegovina Army has been authorized to announce the 
following: 
  Representatives of the Bosnia-Herzegovina Army did not take 
part in the signing of the agreement, although an offer was made 
to them. They were not obliged to take part because the 
agreement is not in line with UN Resolution 913 and NATO's 
ultimatum, which clearly specify the obligations assumed by 
UNPROFOR and the Serbian aggressor side. This makes it clear to 
UNPROFOR representatives that the Bosnia-Herzegovina Army will 
be ready to discuss the implementation of UN Resolution 913 and 
NATO's ultimatum in the future. 
  The situation in the field shows that the Serb aggressors 
have not fulfilled all obligations specified in the above 
mentioned documents. Among other things, they have not 
withdrawn military units and weapons from the 3-km exclusion 
zone around the town center. Furthermore, the aggressors' heavy 
weapons are still in the 20-km zone around Gorazde and are not 
under UNPROFOR's control. There are one tank, six howitzers, 
seven [word indistinct], one self-propelled weapon, one 100-mm 
cannon, and three antiaircraft guns in the 20-km zone. The 
complete evacuation of the wounded has not been made possible, 
and living conditions of the residents in the protected area 
have not improved. 
  We stress that representatives of the Bosnia-Herzegovina 
Army 
[break in reception] are ready to discuss the resolution of the 
situation on the Bosnia-Herzegovina battlefields and other 
decisions that will be based on UN and NATO resolutions. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

