<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbs: Cease-Fire Observed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Serbs: Cease-Fire Observed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2305105694 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1026 GMT 23 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2305105694 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Belgrade, May 23 (TANJUG) -- BBC radio on Monday 
quoted U.N. sources as saying that the Bosnian Serbs are fully 
respecting the ceasefire agreement for Gorazde, Muslim enclave 
in southeast Bosnia, which the Muslims refused to sign. The 
representatives of the Bosnian Serbs and the U.N. Protection 
Force (UNPROFOR) on Saturday signed an annex to the agreement on 
a ceasefire and the cessetion of hostilities in the region of 
Gorazde. But the Muslims refused to sign it, as confirmed by 
the UNPROFOR Command for Bosnia. 
  In a program monitored in Belgrade, BBC radio cited an 
unnamed senior U.N. official in Sarajevo that the respect of the 
ceasefire in Gorazde `enables the deployment of the U.N. troops 
in areas from where the Serbs have withdrawn.' The only 
potential problem is the attempt of the local Muslims to use the 
withdrawl of the Serb forces and sieze the regions they 
previously controlled, which is not allowed under the relevant 
U.N. resolutions, the radio said. 
  It quoted UNPROFOR as saying that armed Bosnian Serb police 
has pulled out of the northern part of Gorazde to 3 km from the 
exclusion zone, while the remainder of the Serbs in the eastern 
parts should withdraw within the next 24 hours. The Bosnian 
Serbs in late April pulled out their heavy weapons to 20 km and 
the infantry to 3 km away from the centre of Gorazde with the 
aim of reaching a peaceful solution to the crisis caused by the 
Muslims who launched a major offensive from this 
`U.N.-designated safe area' in March. 
  Only the Bosnian Serb police remained in the Serb villages 
near Gorazde to allow the local inhabitants to safely return to 
their homes. Some 15,000 Muslims from Gorazde, which should 
have been demilitarized last May, in late March launched an 
offensive on Serb territories. In the face of a total defeat 
from a Serb counterattack, NATO on April 10-11 bombed Serb 
positions close to this town. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

