<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbs Demand Investigation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Serbs Demand Investigation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2205141194 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1355 GMT 22 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2205141194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Brcko, May 22 (TANJUG) -- Colonel Slavko Guzvic of 
the Bosnian Serb Army on Sunday insisted with the command of the 
U.N. Protection Force (UNPROFOR) in war-torn Bosnia-Herzegovina 
to publish an official report about the attack on the Serb town 
of Brcko in northern Bosnia on Saturday [21 May]. A team of the 
U.N. military observers in Brcko, headed by British Captain Sean 
Fawcett, on Saturday inspected the scene of the attack and 
established from where it had come, Colonel Guzvic told TANJUG. 
  While inspecting the place where the first shell had landed, 
Captain Fawcett and his team found the remnants of a rocket 
fired from a multiple rocket launcher which had visible Croatian 
Army markings on it. Five people were seriously wounded, 
including a one year-old girl, in the simulataneous shelling of 
Brcko from the Croat-held village of Vucilovac eight kilometres 
west of Brcko and from the territory of neighbouring Croatia. 
  Brcko is situated at the neck of the strategic corridor 
along 
the Sava river which links the western and the eastern parts of 
the Bosnian Serb republic. The material damage from the latest 
attack is considerable. 
  Captain Fawcett declined to comment on the attack and said 
he 
would submit a detailed report on it to his command. 

</TEXT>

