<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Muslims, Croats Trade Accusations of Attacks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Muslims, Croats Trade Accusations of Attacks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2105132294 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1242 GMT 21 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2105132294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Belgrade, May 21 (TANJUG) -- Tension between Croats 
and Moslems in northern Herzegovina is rising again, with the 
two sides exchanging accusations for a series of armed 
incidents. Two Bosnian Croat soldiers were shot dead on a local 
road northeast of Prozor on Friday, Croatian Radio on Saturday 
quotes U.N. sources as saying. The Moslems, on the other side, 
say the Croats are to blame for renewed tension between the two 
sides. Moslem-controlled Radio Sarajevo says that Bosnian Croat 
forces on Saturday sprayed Moslem positions in the Neretvica 
River valley with small arms fire. 
  The same source reports heavy Croat troop concentrations in 
the area of Doljani near Jablanica, which serves as a buffer 
zone between the Moslem and Croat troops in northern Herzegovina. 
  Bosnian Croats and Moslems, erstwhile allies in the war 
against the local Serbs, first started fighting each other in 
northern Herzegovina in October 1992. The conflicts escalated 
in full-size war in the spring of 1993. 
  After a year of fierce fighting for territories with mixed 
populations in southern and central Bosnia-Herzegovina, the 
Moslems and Croats yielded to U.S. pressure and on March 18 
signed an agreement to form a binational federation. In 
practice, however, the two sides have renewed hostilities and 
their federation agreement seems to be nothing but a dead letter. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

