<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mosque Razed in Croat-Controlled Vitez </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mosque Razed in Croat-Controlled Vitez </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2105160994 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1515 GMT 21 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2105160994 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Banja Luka, May 21 (TANJUG) -- A mosque in the 
Moslem settlement Grbavica in the central Bosnian town of Vitez 
was levelled with the ground on Friday evening, on the eve of 
the Moslem religious holiday of Kurban Bairam, the Croat radio 
of Herzeg-Bosnia reported on Saturday [21 May]. 
  The destroyed mosque was in the area controlled by the 
Bosnian Croats Army (HVO). There are no details about 
perpetrators but an investigation is expected, the announcement 
said. `This terrible incident, which happened on the eve of the 
major Moslem religious holiday of Kurban Bairam, has 
deteriorated the already tense relations between Moslems and 
Croats in the area of Vitez,' the Croat Radio said. Only a few 
hours before explosive was planted, Moslem troops were 
celebrating the coming of Kurban Bairam by shooting on the 
positions of a HVO brigade in the area of Vitez, the radio said. 
  The Bosnian Croats and Moslems were fighting fiercly from 
last spring (over territories with mixed population in central 
and southern Bosnia-Herzegovina) to early February, when, under 
strong U.S. pressure, they signed an accord on their federation 
in Bosnia-Herzegovina supposed to grow into a confederation with 
neighbouring Croatia. 
  Relations between Croats and Moslems are, however, still 
very 
strained, and clashes and incidents do happen increasingly 
often. Apart from Vitez, mosques had been destroyed by Bosnian 
Croats in Zepca, Kiseljak, western Mostar, and Livno, all in the 
Croat republic of Herzeg Bosnia. 

</TEXT>

