<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bosnian Croats Introduce Currency of Croatia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bosnian Croats Introduce Currency of Croatia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2205131394 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1231 GMT 22 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2205131394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, May 22 (TANJUG) -- The government of the 
Bosnian Croat republic of Herceg-Bosnia [as received] has 
decided to introduce a new currency as of June 1 -- the kuna. 
The kuna, which is the national currency of neighbouring 
Croatia, will replace the Croatian dinar, which has so far been 
in circulation in Herceg-Bosnia too. 
  Despite strong protests, the government in Zagreb has 
decided 
to reintroduce the kuna, the national currency of the Nazi 
puppet independent state of Croatia which existed during World 
War Two. The opponents of the Croatian Government's decision 
argue the kuna will only link Croatia with its infamous Nazi 
past. The Moslem government in Sarajevo has still not reacted 
to Herceg-Bosnia's move. 
  After almost a year of fierce battles, Bosnian Moslems and 
Croats in mid-March yielded to U.S. pressure and signed a 
federation agreement. The constitution of their binational 
state in Bosnia, which should subsequently form a confederation 
with neighbouring Croatia, envisages a single federal currency. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-55818 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu099_i_94016" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-099 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   General on Croat View of Federation Defense </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    General on Croat View of Federation Defense </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2205152594 Zagreb VECERNJI LIST in Serbo-Croatian 21 May 
94 p 8 </F>

<F P=103> AU2205152594 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb VECERNJI LIST </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [HINA report: "The Home Guard as a Basis"] </F>
  [Text] Sarajevo -- "The Joint Command of the Croatian 
Defense Council [HVO] and the Bosnia-Herzegovina Army is 
organizing a contemporary type of defense based on the examples 
set forth by the military organization of West European 
countries with the ultimate aim of joining organizations such as 
the `Partnership for Peace'. As a federal army, we could be 
among the first to be accepted into this organization," General 
Ante Roso, HVO representative in the Joint Command of the 
Federation that has recently become operational in Sarajevo, 
told Sarajevo OSLOBODJENJE on Thursday [19 May]. 
  According to General Roso, the Croatian side has proposed 
that the home guard be the basis of the Federation's future 
defense. "In this way, neither would the Croats disarm the 
Bosniaks, nor would the Bosniaks disarm the Croats." The other 
component of the defense system would be the regular army, in 
which 18 to 25 year olds -- male and female -- would serve a 10 
to 12 month term, said General Roso, and added that, for 
example, a student could serve his or her term in some 
institute, because "carrying arms is not the only way to serve 
in the army...." 
  The third component of the Federation's defense would be 
professional brigades for interventions and border units. The 
Joint Command of the HVO and the Bosnia-Herzegovina Army in 
Sarajevo is for the time being not making any decisions on 
combat activities, and it does not have the authority to 
directly command the forces. The Command creates conditions for 
maintaining the current cease-fire, the safety of 
communications, and the restoration of trust between people, 
said General Roso. 

</TEXT>

