<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Krajisnik: No Federation on Serbian Territory </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Krajisnik: No Federation on Serbian Territory </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2205181694 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1806 GMT 22 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2205181694 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Srbinje, May 22 (TANJUG) -- Bosnian Serb Parliament 
President Momcilo Krajisnik said on Sunday that the Bosnian 
Moslems and Croats in Bosnia-Herzegovina could make agreements 
and tailor the future federation to suit them, but they could 
not do that on Serb ethnic territories. 
  The Serbs would not allow a Moslem-Croat federation to be 
formed on their own land, Krajisnik said in Srbinje (formerly 
Foca) at a local ceremony. The Bosnian Moslems and Croats on 
March 18, without the participation of the Serb side and under 
strong U.S. pressure, signed an accord on a dual federation 
which would later enter a confederation with neighbouring 
Croatia. A federation was set up in this way, with no clearly 
defined territory. 
  Work is in progress on settling the issue of territorial 
division in Bosnia. In Vienna, the Moslems and Croats agreed on 
a proposal allocating 58 per cent of the territories to a 
Moslem-Croat federation and 42 per cent to the Serb side, but 
this was not accepted by the Serbs. According to the prewar 
land registers, the Bosnian Serbs owned 64 per cent and after 
the two-year old war they now control about 70 per cent of the 
Bosnian territory. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-55820 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu099_i_94018" </HT>


