<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Klaus Offer Rejected </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Klaus Offer Rejected </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2205131994 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 1200 
GMT 22 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2205131994 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Czech </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] The Sudeten German congress culminated in 
Nuremberg today. Our correspondent Jiri Halousek reports from 
there. [passage omitted] 
  [Correspondent] In his speech today Franz Neubauer, chairman 
of the Sudeten German Landsmannschaft, rejected Czech Prime 
Minister Vaclav Klaus's view that Sudeten Germans might be 
individually granted -- in some circumstances -- the right to 
return to their former homeland. Franz Neubauer said this was 
not sufficient as the Sudeten Germans had not been expelled 
individually, but collectively. 
  The congress concluded with a speech by Bavarian Prime 
Minister Edmund Stoiber. He said relations between Germany and 
Bavaria on one side and the Czech Republic on the other had 
developed significantly in the last few years. However, a 
political dialogue of the Czech cabinet and parliament with 
elected officials of the Sudeten German Landsmannschaft was 
still missing. Only its introduction would make these relations 
really good. This is why Edmund Stoiber proposed to open such a 
dialogue next year, exactly 50 years from the end of the Second 
World War and the start of the Sudeten Germans' expulsion from 
our country. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

