<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Support for Sudeten Germans </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Support for Sudeten Germans </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2205182294 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 1600 
GMT 22 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2205182294 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Czech </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] The 45th Sudeten German Days culminated in 
Nuremberg in Bavaria today. Our correspondent in Germany, Jiri 
Halousek, filed this telephone dispatch. 
  [Begin Halousek recording] [passage omitted] One of the 
first 
speakers to address the main gathering in the Franken Halle at 
the Nueremberg trade fair was Imrich Kruzliak, adviser to the 
Slovak president. Kruzliak conveyed to the Sudeten Germans' 
greetings from Slovakia and said that the Sudeten German issue 
must not be swept under the carpet for political reasons. 
  Afterward, Federal Interior Minister Manfred Kanther 
emphasized that Sudeten Germans had to be included, in the 
spirit of friendship, in future German-Czech relations. At the 
same time, he gave them an assurance of support by the 
Bonn-based Federal Government. 
  Bavarian Minister-President Edmund Stoiber also voiced 
support for the Sudeten German Landesmannschaft. He recalled 
that this year it was precisely 40 years since Bavaria took over 
the patronage of Sudeten Germans. Edmund Stoiber went on to say 
that in recent years there has been a comprehensive development 
of relations between Bavaria and Germany and the Czech Republic. 
In order to describe them as good, it is apparently still 
necessary that the Czech Government and parliament open a 
political dialogue with the elected representatives of the 
Sudeten German Landesmannschaft. 
  The Bavarian minister-president went on to say that he 
discussed this issue with Czech Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus in 
August last year. At that time he gained the impression that 
Vaclav Klaus was going to give serious consideration to his 
proposal. That is why he is supposedly waiting for a signal 
from the Czech side. [passage omitted] [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

