<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Law on Foreign Investment Adopted in Parliament </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Law on Foreign Investment Adopted in Parliament </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2005155094 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1221 GMT 20 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2005155094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, May 20 (TANJUG) -- Firms founded with 
foreign capital in the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia will have 
to adjust by the end of the year their operations to the new law 
on foreign investments which was adopted by the Yugoslav 
parliament on Thursday [20 May]. Full effect of the law is 
expected after the alleviation or lifting of the economic 
sanctions imposed by the United Nations Security Council on May 
30, 1992. 
  As explained by the federal government, the new law is 
expected to ensure greater legal security for foreign investors, 
grant additional facilities for those who are ready to invest in 
the Yugoslav economy and simplify the investment procedure. The 
law rules that foreigners can found firms in Yugoslavia, invest 
capital in domestic firms, open company branches and buy shares 
and concessions for exploitation of natural resourses. 
  Foreign investors will also be able to import equipment and 
materials for building firms in Yugoslavia tax-free. Foreigners 
are only not allowed to hold more than 49 percent of the shares 
in strategically important branches of industry, such as the 
miltiary industry. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-55850 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu099_y_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-099 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  20 May 1994 </DATE1>

