<F P=100> THE FORMER YUGOSLAV REPUBLIC OF MACEDONIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crvenkovski on `Progress' With Greece </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Crvenkovski on `Progress' With Greece </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2005195394 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1903 GMT 20 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2005195394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Skopje, 20 May (TANJUG) -- Macedonian Foreign 
Minister Stevo Crvenkovski returned to Skopje this evening after 
a several-day visit to New York, where he had several meetings 
with Cyrus Vance, UN mediator in the dispute with Greece, and 
with the U.S. President's special envoy, Matthew Nimitz. In a 
statement for the press immediately on arrival at Skopje 
airport, Crvenkovski said that certain progress has been 
achieved in the dispute with Greece. Namely, the talks are 
focused on overall bilateral relations and contacts between the 
two countries are being maintained without Greece's three 
well-known conditions. However, Crvenkovski concluded, it is 
hard to say how things will develop further. He also announced 
that Nimitz will soon be visiting Skopje. 

</TEXT>

