<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Krajina Official: Tudjman `Nervous' About War </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Krajina Official: Tudjman `Nervous' About War </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2205143994 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1347 GMT 22 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2205143994 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Kragujevac, 22 May -- Borislav Mikelic, prime 
minister of the Republic of Serb Krajina, told Kragujevac Radio 
today that Croatian President Franjo Tudjman "has become 
nervous," about the internal problems in his party and that 
"there is nothing else for him to do but to take up the war 
option." 
  Commenting on Tudjman's threat that "he will use all 
available means to reintegrate the rebel Serbs into Croatia," 
Mikelic said that the Republic of Serb Krajina would also use 
all of its available resources to defend all things Serbian and 
which have been Serbian for centuries. Adding that the defense 
of the republic of Serb Krajina "is not what it was when 
Miljevci plateau and Divoselo were attacked," and that Serbs 
would no longer lodge complaints with the UNPROFOR [UN 
Protection Force] if Croats attack any of their villages, 
Mikelic said: "Our strength is now tenfold compared to earlier 
years." 
  Dwelling on the statements from Croatia that it would not 
extend UNPROFOR's mandate, Mikelic said the territory in 
question did not belong to Croatia but to the republic of Serb 
Krajina and that the international forces could stay there for 
two years because the Serbs want peace. "Croatia's behavior as a 
whole best illustrates why Serbs cannot and do not want to live 
with the Croats any longer," he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

